## Installation

Install the React package and the core Convo-Lang package.

``` sh
npm i @convo-lang/convo-lang-react @convo-lang/convo-lang
```

You will typically also want a Convo-Lang-compatible backend endpoint if you are calling hosted models over HTTP.

---

## Basic usage

The smallest useful example is a `ConvoView` pointed at a Convo-Lang endpoint.

``` tsx
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

export default function MyPage()
{
    return (
        <div className="h-[700px]">
            <ConvoView
                className="h-full"
                httpEndpoint="http://localhost:7222/api/convo-lang"
            />
        </div>
    );
}
```

This gives you:
- a conversation UI
- a default theme
- a default input
- a default message list
- a default controller
- a connection to your HTTP completion backend

---

## Slightly more realistic example

``` tsx
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

const template=/*convo*/`
\> system
You are a helpful assistant for a software team.
Be concise and useful.

\> assistant
Hi! What are you working on today?
`;

export default function HelpDeskPage()
{
    return (
        <div className="h-[800px]">
            <ConvoView
                className="h-full"
                httpEndpoint="http://localhost:7222/api/convo-lang"
                template={template}
                inputPlaceholder="Ask a question"
                enableStreaming
                enableMarkdown
                enableSlashCommands
                suggestionsLocation="before-input"
            />
        </div>
    );
}
```

---

## What ConvoView renders

By default `ConvoView` can render:

- user messages
- assistant messages
- system messages
- function definitions
- function/tool calls
- function/tool results
- RAG messages
- suggestion messages
- component-rendered messages
- streaming messages
- source/code view of the conversation

---

## Core mental model

`ConvoView` is a wrapper around a `ConversationUiCtrl`.

### If you do nothing
`ConvoView` creates its own controller.

### If you need control
You can pass your own `ConversationUiCtrl` through the `ctrl` prop.

This gives you two modes:

- **simple mode**
  - use `ConvoView` as a self-contained chat component

- **advanced mode**
  - create and control the conversation externally
  - share the same controller across multiple components
  - build custom layouts around the same underlying conversation

---

## Common use cases

### 1. Standard AI chat window

Use `ConvoView` as a single full chat experience with a prompt template and endpoint.

Best for:
- internal assistants
- support chat
- workflow copilots
- general-purpose chat apps

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    className="h-full"
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    template={template}
    enableStreaming
    enableMarkdown
/>
```

---

### 2. Branded chat UI with custom styling

Use `theme` and `className` to match your product design.

Best for:
- productized copilots
- customer-facing assistants
- embedded SaaS support tools

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    theme=\{{
        convoViewClassName:'bg-background text-foreground rounded-3xl',
        messageClassName:'rounded-2xl border',
        inputContainerClassName:'rounded-3xl border bg-background',
        inputSubmitButtonClassName:'rounded-full bg-primary text-primary-foreground',
    }}
/>
```

---

### 3. Prompt editing and developer tooling

Enable source mode or show source to let users inspect and edit the Convo-Lang conversation.

Best for:
- prompt builders
- internal debugging tools
- AI workflow editors
- educational tools

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    showSource
    showInputWithSource
/>
```

You can also control the source display mode with `sourceMode`.

---

### 4. Tool-driven assistants

Use Convo-Lang functions, extern functions, and optional custom renderers for tool calls and results.

Best for:
- agents that call APIs
- workflow automation UIs
- business process assistants
- artifact creation tools

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    externFunctions=\{{
        createTicket(title:string,priority:string){
            return {id:'T-100',title,priority};
        }
    }}
    showFunctions
    showResults
/>
```

---

### 5. Artifact or side-panel layouts

Redirect messages or use render targets to split the experience into multiple panels.

Best for:
- Claude-style artifact layouts
- side-by-side results
- document viewers
- generated app previews

The example app in `nextjs-tailwinds/pages/index.tsx` demonstrates a related pattern by rendering generated HTML tools in a side panel.

---

### 6. Voice-first chat

Enable recording, live mode, and optional read-back of responses.

Best for:
- mobile-friendly assistants
- hands-free workflows
- accessibility-focused experiences
- real-time voice interaction

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableAudioRecorder
    enableLiveMode
    readResponses
/>
```

---

### 7. Multi-modal chat with attachments

Allow users to attach images or other accepted file types.

Best for:
- visual assistants
- image understanding
- media analysis
- document/image workflows

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableAttachment
    acceptAttachmentTypes="image/*"
    maxImageWidth={1024}
/>
```

---

## Quick start examples

## Example: simple chat

``` tsx
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

export function SimpleChat()
{
    return (
        <ConvoView
            className="h-full"
            httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
        />
    );
}
```

---

## Example: chat with a prompt template

``` tsx
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

const template=/*convo*/`
\> define
appName='Acme Support'

\> system
You are the official assistant for \{{appName}}.
Always be polite and concise.

\> assistant
Hi, how can I help you today?
`;

export function TemplatedChat()
{
    return (
        <ConvoView
            className="h-full"
            httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
            template={template}
            enableStreaming
            enableMarkdown
        />
    );
}
```

---

## Example: use a default conversation value

`defaultValue` can seed the conversation source directly.

``` tsx
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

const defaultValue=/*convo*/`
\> assistant
Hello, how can I help?

\> user
Show me an example of Convo-Lang in action
`.trim()+'\n';

export function SeededChat()
{
    return (
        <ConvoView
            className="h-full"
            httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
            defaultValue={defaultValue}
        />
    );
}
```

---

## Example: use extern functions

Extern functions let the conversation call into your app code.

``` tsx
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

export function ToolChat()
{
    return (
        <ConvoView
            className="h-full"
            httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
            showFunctions
            showResults
            externFunctions=\{{
                saveTodo(title:string)
                {
                    return {
                        success:true,
                        id:'todo_123',
                        title,
                    };
                },
            }}
            template={/*convo*/`
# Save a todo item
\> extern saveTodo(
    title:string
)

\> assistant
Tell me about a task you want to save.
`}
        />
    );
}
```

---

## Example: model selector

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableModelSelector
    selectableModels={[
        'gpt-5',
        'claude-3-7-sonnet',
        'deepseek-r1',
    ]}
/>
```

If `selectableModels` is not provided, `ConvoView` can attempt to load the available models from the conversation backend.

---

## Example: suggestions near the input

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    suggestionsLocation="before-input"
    forceInlineSuggestionsLocation
/>
```

This can show suggestions:
- inline in the message stream
- before the input
- after the input
- or both inline and near the input

---

## Example: audio, live mode, and response playback

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableAudioRecorder
    enableLiveMode
    readResponses
/>
```

---

## Example: custom input renderer

Use `renderInput` if you want to fully replace the default input UI.

``` tsx
import { Button } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    noInput
    renderInput={(ctrl)=>(
        <div className="p-4 border-t flex gap-2">
            <Button onClick={()=>ctrl.appendUiMessageAsync('Hello')}>
                Say hello
            </Button>
            <Button onClick={()=>ctrl.appendUiMessageAsync('Summarize this conversation')}>
                Summarize
            </Button>
        </div>
    )}
/>
```

---

## Example: use your own controller

``` tsx
import { ConversationUiCtrl } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang';
import { useMemo } from 'react';
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

export function ControlledChat()
{
    const ctrl=useMemo(()=>new ConversationUiCtrl({
        template:`
\> system
You are a planning assistant.
`,
    }),[]);

    return (
        <ConvoView
            ctrl={ctrl}
            httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
            enableStreaming
        />
    );
}
```

Use this when:
- multiple components need the same conversation
- you want external lifecycle control
- you want to set controller state directly

---

## Example: get the created controller

``` tsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import { ConversationUiCtrl } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang';
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

export function GetControllerExample()
{
    const [ctrl,setCtrl]=useState<ConversationUiCtrl|null>(null);

    return (
        <div className="h-full flex flex-col">
            <div className="p-2 border-b">
                <button onClick={()=>ctrl?.appendUiMessageAsync('Write a haiku')}>
                    Ask for haiku
                </button>
            </div>
            <ConvoView
                className="flex-1"
                httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
                getCtrl={setCtrl}
            />
        </div>
    );
}
```

---

## Example: custom attachment picker

`browseAttachmentRequested` lets you replace the default file input behavior.

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableAttachment
    acceptAttachmentTypes="image/*"
    browseAttachmentRequested={async (accept)=>{
        console.log('Open custom picker for',accept);
        return null;
    }}
/>
```

Return one of:
- `File`
- `Blob`
- base64 data URL string
- `null`
- `undefined`

---

## Example: custom theme

``` tsx
import { ConvoView } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang-react';

export function ThemedChat()
{
    return (
        <ConvoView
            httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
            theme=\{{
                convoViewClassName:'relative flex flex-col bg-background text-foreground',
                rowClassName:'flex items-start gap-3',
                messageClassName:'rounded-2xl border p-3',
                assistantMessageClassName:'bg-muted',
                userMessageClassName:'bg-primary text-primary-foreground',
                inputAreaClassName:'absolute left-0 right-0 bottom-0 p-4',
                inputContainerClassName:'rounded-3xl border bg-background',
                inputClassName:'flex-1 p-3 outline-none resize-none',
                inputSubmitButtonClassName:'size-8 rounded-full bg-primary text-primary-foreground',
            }}
        />
    );
}
```

---

## Props overview

Below is a practical guide to the main `ConvoView` props.

## Controller and lifecycle

### `ctrl?:ConversationUiCtrl`
Provide your own controller instead of letting `ConvoView` create one.

### `getCtrl?:(ctrl:ConversationUiCtrl)=>void`
Called with the active controller.

### `ctrlOptions?:ConversationUiCtrlOptions`
Options passed to an auto-created controller.

### `appendTrigger?:ConvoUiAppendTrigger`
Programmatically append content or trigger completion.

Useful when:
- external UI elements need to inject messages
- you want button-driven message appends
- you want to trigger completions from outside the chat input

### `beforeCreateExeCtx?:BeforeCreateConversationExeCtx|null|undefined`
Hook that runs before the execution context is created.

Good for:
- last-second variable insertion
- modifying the conversation before completion
- injecting app state

### `enabledInitMessage?:boolean`
Allows initialization messages to trigger completions on mount.

### `onVarsChange?:(vars:Record<string,any>)=>void`
Observe conversation variable changes.

---

## Prompt and template configuration

### `template?:string`
Main Convo-Lang source template.

### `templatePrefix?:string`
Prepends raw Convo-Lang source before `template`.

### `defaultValue?:string`
Sets the current conversation source.

### `imports?:string|string[]`
Imports inserted into the conversation source as `@import` statements.

### `modules?:ConvoModule[]`
Modules to register with the conversation.

### `modulesRefreshKey?:string|number`
Force module refresh when modules change.

### `defaultVars?:Record<string,any>`
Default variable values inserted into the conversation.

### `externFunctions?:Record<string,(...params:any[])=>any>`
Backs `extern` functions declared in the Convo-Lang source.

---

## Backend and model configuration

### `httpEndpoint?:string`
Convo-Lang-compatible API endpoint.

When provided, `ConvoView` wires this endpoint to:
- completion service
- transcription service
- text-to-speech service
- embeddings service

### `enableModelSelector?:boolean`
Shows a model dropdown in the UI.

### `selectableModels?:string[]`
Limit model choices to a fixed list.

### `enableStreaming?:boolean`
Enables streaming responses.

---

## Rendering and display behavior

### `showSource?:boolean`
Switch from chat UI to source view.

### `sourceMode?:ConvoEditorMode`
Controls what source content is shown.

Typical modes include things like:
- code
- flat
- text
- model
- vars
- imports
- modules

### `showInputWithSource?:boolean`
If `true`, keep the input visible while in source mode.

### `showFunctions?:boolean`
Render functions/function messages as bubbles.

### `showResults?:boolean`
Render variable assignments and result messages as bubbles.

### `showSystem?:boolean`
Render system messages as bubbles.

### `enableMarkdown?:ConvoMarkdownEnableState`
Enable markdown rendering for user messages, assistant messages, or both.

### `disableDefaultFunctionCallRender?:boolean`
Turn off the default function call renderer.

Useful if you want all tool rendering to be custom.

### `disableScroll?:boolean`
Disable scrolling in message or source views.

### `messageBottomPadding?:string|null`
Extra space at the bottom of the message list.

Useful when:
- using floating inputs
- preventing the last message from sitting behind the input

---

## Suggestions

### `suggestionsLocation?:'inline'|'before-input'|'after-input'`
Controls where suggestion messages render.

### `forceInlineSuggestionsLocation?:boolean`
Keep suggestions inline even when also rendering them near the input.

### `suggestionProps?:Partial<ConvoSuggestionsViewProps>`
Props for the suggestions component near the input.

---

## Message list customization

### `messageListProps?:ConvoMessageViewProps`
Extra props forwarded into the default message list rendering path.

### `ragRenderer?:ConvoRagRenderer`
Custom renderer for RAG messages.

### `componentRenderers?:Record<string,ConvoComponentRenderer>`
Render custom components for embedded components and tool outputs.

### `renderTarget?:string`
Render only messages for a specific target.

### `redirectMessagesView?:(view:any)=>void`
Redirect the rendered messages view outside of the component.

Useful for:
- multi-panel layouts
- detached message rendering
- artifact panels

---

## Input customization

### `renderInput?:(ctrl:ConversationUiCtrl)=>any`
Completely replace the default input UI.

### `noInput?:boolean`
Hide the input entirely.

### `inputProps?:Partial<ConvoInputProps>`
Pass props to the default input component.

### `inputPlaceholder?:string`
Placeholder text for the input.

### `beforeInputStart?:any`
Rendered before the input, at the start of the row above it.

### `beforeInputEnd?:any`
Rendered before the input, at the end of the row above it.

### `afterInputStart?:any`
Rendered after the input, at the start of the row below it.

### `afterInputEnd?:any`
Rendered after the input, at the end of the row below it.

---

## Attachments and media

### `enableAttachment?:boolean`
Enable attachments, typically images.

### `acceptAttachmentTypes?:string`
Accepted file types for the attachment picker.

Default:
``` ts
'image/*'
```

### `browseAttachmentRequested?:(accept:string)=>Promise<File|Blob|string|null|undefined>`
Override the default attachment browser.

### `maxImageWidth?:number`
Max image width before resize.

### `maxImageHeight?:number`
Max image height before resize.

---

## Voice and audio

### `enableAudioRecorder?:boolean`
Enable microphone recording.

### `enableLiveMode?:boolean`
Enable live conversational voice mode.

### `readResponses?:boolean`
Read assistant responses with text-to-speech.

---

## Source view behavior

### `codeInputAutoScrollBehavior?:ScrollBehavior`
Controls auto-scroll behavior in source mode.

### `sourceDarkMode?:boolean|'auto'`
Controls source editor dark mode behavior.

---

## Input change events

### `onInputChange?:(change:ConversationInputChange)=>void`
Called when the input changes.

This applies to:
- chat input
- source editor input

The callback receives:

``` ts
export interface ConversationInputChange
{
    type:'chat'|'source';
    value:string;
}
```

---

## Theming

### `theme?:ConvoViewTheme`
Theme object controlling class names and icons across the entire view.

This is one of the strongest parts of `ConvoView` because nearly every visual surface can be themed.

Theme categories include:
- root layout
- icons
- messages
- rows
- markdown/plain text
- suggestions
- message list
- loader
- input
- attachment buttons
- audio recorder UI
- task display
- function call display
- RAG display
- source view

A large set of theme fields is supported. Examples include:

- `convoViewClassName`
- `messageClassName`
- `assistantMessageClassName`
- `userMessageClassName`
- `rowClassName`
- `inputContainerClassName`
- `inputClassName`
- `inputSubmitButtonClassName`
- `suggestionButtonClassName`
- `functionCallClassName`
- `sourceViewClassName`
- icon fields such as `assistantIcon`, `userIcon`, `loaderIcon`

The default theme is provided internally via `getConvoViewTheme('default')`.

---

## Feature-by-feature guide

## 1. Streaming

Enable streaming with:

``` tsx
<ConvoView enableStreaming httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang" />
```

Benefits:
- faster perceived response times
- better chat UX
- visible progressive generation
- supports streaming function-call rendering

---

## 2. Markdown rendering

Enable markdown rendering with:

``` tsx
<ConvoView enableMarkdown httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang" />
```

This allows assistant or user messages to render markdown using the configured markdown renderer.

Useful for:
- docs assistants
- code assistants
- formatted summaries
- rich response UIs

---

## 3. Function/tool calls

Convo-Lang functions map naturally into the UI.

You can:
- show function definitions with `showFunctions`
- show result bubbles with `showResults`
- allow default function call rendering
- replace default rendering with custom components
- stream function-call output

Example:

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    showFunctions
    showResults
/>
```

---

## 4. System message visibility

System messages are usually part of the prompt rather than the user-facing UI. For debugging or developer tools, you can expose them.

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    showSystem
/>
```

Useful for:
- debugging prompts
- teaching Convo-Lang
- prompt engineering tools
- admin/debug builds

---

## 5. Source mode

Source mode swaps the chat list for a code/source-oriented view of the conversation.

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    showSource
    showInputWithSource
/>
```

This is especially useful because Convo-Lang is plain text. Users can inspect or edit the underlying conversation script directly.

Good for:
- prompt labs
- debugging
- developer tools
- educational demos
- AI workflow editing

---

## 6. Suggestions

Suggestions can be rendered:
- inline in the message stream
- above the input
- below the input

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    suggestionsLocation="after-input"
/>
```

---

## 7. Attachments

Enable file/image attachments:

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableAttachment
    acceptAttachmentTypes="image/*"
/>
```

This is ideal when using Convo-Lang with:
- vision models
- image analysis tools
- multi-modal assistants

---

## 8. Audio recorder

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableAudioRecorder
/>
```

This enables the recording UI and transcription flow.

---

## 9. Live mode

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableAudioRecorder
    enableLiveMode
/>
```

Live mode is for direct speech-driven interaction with the LLM.

---

## 10. Read responses aloud

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    readResponses
/>
```

This enables TTS response playback when configured services are available.

---

## 11. Model selection

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableModelSelector
/>
```

This is useful for:
- model comparison
- debugging
- user-controlled model choice
- internal evaluation tools

---

## 12. Slash commands

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    enableSlashCommands
/>
```

This enables slash-command usage through the UI controller.

---

## 13. Render targets and redirected views

These features let you break the UI apart into more advanced layouts.

### `renderTarget`
Filters which messages render in this instance.

### `redirectMessagesView`
Lets you render the message view elsewhere.

These are advanced but powerful for:
- split-pane apps
- side panels
- artifacts
- embedded tool surfaces

---

## 14. Custom component renderers

If your Convo-Lang messages or function results map to named components, you can render custom React output.

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    componentRenderers=\{{
        chart:{
            render(comp,ctx){
                return <div>Custom chart renderer</div>;
            },
        },
    }}
/>
```

This is one of the biggest reasons to use ConvoView for serious AI products instead of generic chat UIs.

It lets your AI output become app UI.

---

## 15. RAG rendering

You can override how RAG messages display.

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    ragRenderer={(message)=>(
        <div className="text-sm opacity-80">
            Retrieved: {message.content}
        </div>
    )}
/>
```

---

## Building blocks around ConvoView

While `ConvoView` is the primary component, it is composed of smaller pieces.

You usually do not need to use these directly at first, but it helps to know what exists.

## `ConvoInput`
Default chat input UI.

Features include:
- text entry
- submit button
- attachments
- image previews
- audio recording
- live mode controls
- transcription status
- custom props via `inputProps`

Use `renderInput` to replace it.

---

## `ConvoMessageListView`
Renders the conversation message stream.

Supports:
- message rendering
- streaming messages
- auto-scroll
- suggestion suppression
- custom status indicator
- markdown and function rendering options

Use `redirectMessagesView` when you want to move this outside of `ConvoView`.

---

## `ConvoSourceView`
Renders the conversation as source/code.

Supports:
- source editing
- alternate source modes
- scrolling behavior
- dark mode behavior
- submission from source mode

---

## `ConvoSuggestionsView`
Renders suggestion buttons near the input.

---

## `ConvoModelSelector`
Renders the model dropdown when enabled.

---

## Hooks and helpers

The library also exposes hooks that are useful when building around `ConvoView`.

## `useConversationUiCtrl`
Access the current `ConversationUiCtrl` from context.

## `useConversation`
Get the active conversation.

## `useConversationMessages`
Get flattened messages.

## `useConvoTheme`
Get the active `ConvoViewTheme`.

These are useful when building adjacent custom UI around the main `ConvoView`.

---

## Working from the example app

The example in `examples/nextjs-tailwinds/pages/index.tsx` is a strong reference because it shows how `ConvoView` behaves in a real page.

Highlights from that example:

- the page wraps `ConvoView` in a full-height bordered container
- the theme is changed externally using page-level state
- multiple booleans toggle major features
- an `externFunctions` entry is used to create HTML tools
- generated artifact content is rendered in a side panel iframe
- `defaultValue` seeds a real working Convo-Lang conversation
- audio, live mode, markdown, attachments, streaming, and model selection are all exposed with toggles

A simplified version of that usage looks like this:

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="http://localhost:7222/api/convo-lang"
    className="flex-1"
    inputPlaceholder="Ask something cool"
    enableMarkdown={enableMarkdown}
    enableSlashCommands={enableSlashCommands}
    suggestionsLocation="before-input"
    forceInlineSuggestionsLocation
    showFunctions={showFunctions}
    showResults={showResults}
    showSystem={showSystem}
    enableStreaming={enableStreaming}
    enableAttachment={enableAttachment}
    enableModelSelector={enableModelSelector}
    enableAudioRecorder={enableAudioRecorder}
    enableLiveMode={enableLiveMode}
    defaultValue={defaultValue}
    readResponses={readResponses}
    externFunctions=\{{
        createHtmlTool(name:string,content:string)
        {
            return 'created';
        },
    }}
/>
```

This is a very good “everything turned on” reference.

---

## Recommended adoption path

If you are new to `ConvoView`, start in this order:

### Step 1
Render a basic chat:
- `httpEndpoint`
- `className`

### Step 2
Add your Convo-Lang prompt:
- `template`
- `defaultValue`
- `externFunctions`

### Step 3
Improve the UX:
- `enableStreaming`
- `enableMarkdown`
- `inputPlaceholder`
- `suggestionsLocation`

### Step 4
Add advanced UI:
- `enableModelSelector`
- `enableAttachment`
- `showSource`
- `showFunctions`
- `showResults`

### Step 5
Add multimodal and voice:
- `enableAudioRecorder`
- `enableLiveMode`
- `readResponses`

### Step 6
Move into app-specific rendering:
- `componentRenderers`
- `ragRenderer`
- `renderTarget`
- `redirectMessagesView`
- custom `theme`

---

## When to use ConvoView vs a fully custom UI

Use `ConvoView` when you want:
- a complete chat UI quickly
- strong Convo-Lang integration
- support for tools, results, source mode, and voice
- a flexible but batteries-included architecture

Use a fully custom UI when:
- your chat layout is extremely specialized
- you want total control over every surface
- you only need a tiny subset of features

Even in fully custom cases, `ConversationUiCtrl` and the React hooks can still be useful.

---

## Practical patterns

## Pattern: readonly transcript viewer

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    noInput
/>
```

Useful for:
- review screens
- transcript embeds
- historical conversation views

---

## Pattern: floating prompt lab

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    showSource
    showInputWithSource
    sourceDarkMode="auto"
/>
```

Useful for:
- prompt experimentation
- dev tools
- editing prompt flows in-browser

---

## Pattern: support copilot

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    template={supportTemplate}
    enableStreaming
    enableMarkdown
    enableAttachment
    enableModelSelector
/>
```

Useful for:
- customer support
- agent workspaces
- operations consoles

---

## Pattern: voice assistant

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    template={voiceTemplate}
    enableAudioRecorder
    enableLiveMode
    readResponses
/>
```

Useful for:
- kiosks
- accessibility
- hands-free tools
- mobile usage

---

## Pattern: artifact assistant

``` tsx
<ConvoView
    httpEndpoint="/api/convo-lang"
    template={artifactTemplate}
    showFunctions
    showResults
    componentRenderers={componentRenderers}
/>
```

Useful for:
- generated UI
- dashboards
- documents
- code or chart artifacts

---

## Notes and best practices

- Prefer `template` for stable prompt definitions.
- Use `defaultValue` when you want to seed or replace the conversation source.
- Use `externFunctions` for bridging Convo-Lang to app code.
- Turn on `showSystem`, `showFunctions`, and `showResults` in debug builds.
- Use `enableStreaming` for a much better chat experience.
- Use `componentRenderers` when AI output should become interactive UI.
- Use `showSource` and `sourceMode` for prompt debugging and teaching.
- Use `theme` instead of rewriting the component unless you truly need a fully custom layout.
- Use `getCtrl` or `ctrl` when external UI needs to manipulate the conversation directly.

---

## Summary

`ConvoView` is the fastest way to build a full-featured Convo-Lang chat experience in React.

It is especially powerful because it combines:
- a ready-to-use chat UI
- a conversation controller
- first-class Convo-Lang support
- tools, results, RAG, and source-mode support
- multimodal and voice features
- extensive theming and rendering hooks

If you only remember one thing, remember this:

**`ConvoView` is not just a message box. It is a full UI shell for Convo-Lang-powered agents and workflows.**

If you want to see it in action, start with:

- `examples/nextjs-tailwinds/pages/index.tsx`

and then adapt that example to your own prompt, endpoint, tools, and theme.
